<section id="slide-org7d45d5d">
<h2 id="org7d45d5d">1.3 â€“ Given a scenario, use appropriate laptop features.</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-org7d45d5d">
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgaa37e4d">
<h3 id="orgaa37e4d">Docking station</h3>
<ul>
<li>A docking station allows the user to connect their laptop to an external keyboard, display, mouse, and external video cards</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org85b1035">
<h3 id="org85b1035">Port replicator</h3>
<ul>
<li>A port replicator is similar to a docking station, but does not have external expansion cards.
<ul>
<li>A port replicator will allow the laptop to connect to a number of other peripheral devices.</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>


<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images/1-3-PortReplicator.jpg" alt="1-3-PortReplicator.jpg" width="75%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 18: </span>Look at all those ports!</p>
</div>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org2d86d6d">
<h3 id="org2d86d6d">Physical laptop lock and cable lock</h3>
<ul>
<li>One of the advantages of a laptop is also one of its weaknesses.
<ul>
<li>They are light and mobile, which means that they are easier to steal
<ul>
<li>Cable locks are a way of making your laptop more secure.</li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>


<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images/1-3-cableLock2.jpeg" alt="1-3-cableLock2.jpeg" width="45%;">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 19: </span>A cable lock</p>
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org3bd7687">
<h3 id="org3bd7687">Rotating/removable screens</h3>
<ul>
<li>Some laptops have displays that can be rotated or detatched, making them more like tablets.
<ul>
<li>These devices are more likely to have a digital stylus for input.</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images/1-3-Asus-flip.png" alt="1-3-Asus-flip.png" width="50%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 20: </span>ASUS C302 Flip</p>
</div>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
</section>
<section>
<section id="slide-orgd59e62a">
<h2 id="orgd59e62a">1.4 â€“ Compare and contrast characteristics of various types of other mobile devices.</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-orgd59e62a">
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgda570fd">
<h3 id="orgda570fd">Tablets</h3>
<ul>
<li>Tablets, in many ways, are sort of like giant smartphones
<ul>
<li>accomplish the same ends and share similar technologies</li>
<li>Their operating systems can be:
<ul>
<li>Android (an open operating system developed by Google)</li>
<li>or iOS (a proprietary operating system developed by Apple).</li>
<li>Generally measure between 6 and 11 inches diagonally.</li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org24011be">
<h3 id="org24011be">Smartphones</h3>
<ul>
<li>Devices focussed on mobile communication
<ul>
<li>in addition to voice commuication usually have access to email, productivity software, music or video.</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org5d6d0b4">
<h3 id="org5d6d0b4">Wearable technology devices</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org5d6d0b4">
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgd808449">
<h4 id="orgd808449">Smart watches</h4>
<ul>
<li>Like smart phones, only smaller and on your wrist!
<ul>
<li>Wireless ability can include WiFi, cellular, or Bluetooth / local connections to your phone.</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org7100a90">
<h4 id="org7100a90">Fitness monitors</h4>
<ul>
<li>Bands that can fit around your wrist or elsewhere
<ul>
<li>Monitor things such as heartrate and respiration</li>
<li>Then send that data wirelessly to your phone or another computer</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orge1e39a7">
<h4 id="orge1e39a7">VR/AR headsets</h4>
<ul>
<li>Still more promise than reality
<ul>
<li>Designed to replace reality with a computer-generated version
<ul>
<li>Could be used for games or industrial design.</li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org7a609df">
<h3 id="org7a609df">E-readers</h3>
<ul>
<li>Digital devices allowing the reading of books</li>
<li>Share many characteristics with tablets and smartphones.</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org107da6a">
<h3 id="org107da6a">GPS</h3>
<ul>
<li>Now more often incorporated in phones
<ul>
<li>GPS stands for &ldquo;Global Positioning System) and uses satellites to fix your location</li>
<li>Requires power and a view of the sky.</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
</section>
<section>
<section id="slide-org3c44546">
<h2 id="org3c44546">1.5 â€“ Given a scenario, connect and configure accessories and ports of other mobile devices.</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-org3c44546">
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org27e1938">
<h3 id="org27e1938">Connection Types</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org27e1938">
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org9fc90a3">
<h4 id="org9fc90a3">Wired connections</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-org9fc90a3">
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org4bd97b7">
<h5 id="org4bd97b7">Micro-USB / Mini-USB / USB-C</h5>

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images/1-5-MobileDeviceConnectors.jpg" alt="1-5-MobileDeviceConnectors.jpg" width="70%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 21: </span>Different mobile ports and connectors</p>
</div>
<ul>
<li>The timescale of adoption has gone like this: 
<ul>
<li><i>even older connectors</i> &#x2013;&gt; Mini USB-B &#x2013;&gt; Micro USB-B &#x2013;&gt; USB-C</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org6504400">
<h5 id="org6504400">USB connectors</h5>
<ul>
<li><b>USB-B</b>: Mini USB-B found only in older devices today.
<ul>
<li>The EU standardized Micro USB-B for most mobile devices</li>

</ul></li>
<li><b>USB-C</b>: Newer USB format
<ul>
<li>24-pin double-sided USB connector</li>
<li>Symmetrical</li>
<li>Can be used for both hosts and devices</li>
<li>Both USB 3.1 and USB 2.0</li>
<li>Can carry power, data, analog (audio)</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orga4748b1">
<h5 id="orga4748b1">Lightning</h5>
<ul>
<li>Proprietary Apple format
<ul>
<li>8-pin digital signals</li>
<li>Used on iPad, iPhone, iPod</li>
<li>Generally more durable than micro USB-B</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images/1-5-LightningConnector.png" alt="1-5-LightningConnector.png" width="45%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 22: </span>Lightning connector</p>
</div>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgb990962">
<h5 id="orgb990962">Tethering</h5>
<ul>
<li>Allows another device (laptop, desktop, other smartphones) to use your mobile device&rsquo;s internet connection</li>
<li>Tethering can be wired (using USB / Lightning connectors</li>
<li>or wireless, using Bluetooth</li>
<li>Sometimes needs to be specifically enabled by a wireless carrier (Verizon!)</li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org13077a1">
<h5 id="org13077a1">Proprietary vendor-specific ports (communication/power)</h5>
<ul>
<li>Older connectors had diverse shapes and capabilities
<ul>
<li>Different connectors for power, data.</li>

</ul></li>
<li>A maddening situation that was partly sorted out by the EU</li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgb8299c5">
<h4 id="orgb8299c5">Wireless</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-orgb8299c5">
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org298b4b9">
<h5 id="org298b4b9">NFC</h5>
<ul>
<li><b>Near Field Communication</b></li>
<li>Short range wireless communication using 13.56 MHz frequency</li>
<li>Transmits 100-400 kb/s - not much! Slower than Bluetooth</li>
<li>Used for transmitting data between devices (contact info, MP3s, photos)
<ul>
<li>Can communicate with POS terminals for contactless payment - acts like a smart card</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images/1-5-NFCpayment.png" alt="1-5-NFCpayment.png" width="40%" style="float:right;">
</p>
</div>
<ul>
<li>Also used with NFC tags</li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section>

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images/1-5-NFCtag.png" alt="1-5-NFCtag.png" WIDTH="80%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 24: </span>NFC tags and phone</p>
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgcc03502">
<h3 id="orgcc03502">Bluetooth</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-orgcc03502">
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgbbf1817">
<h4 id="orgbbf1817">Enable Bluetooth</h4>
<ul>
<li>Short-range, usually 10 meters or so.  Part of a PAN (personal area network)</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
