<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgc963265">
<h4 id="orgc963265">Laser printer maintenance</h4>
<ul>
<li>Replace toner</li>
<li>Apply maintenance kit</li>
<li>Calibrate</li>
<li>Clean</li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgff72b48">
<h3 id="orgff72b48">Inkjet</h3>
<ul>
<li>Inexpensive in itself, but ink is costly</li>

</ul>


<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images/3-11-InkjetPrinterInsideDiagram.jpg" alt="3-11-InkjetPrinterInsideDiagram.jpg" width="80%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 109: </span>Inkjet printer components - the only terms you need to know are listed below</p>
</div>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org990fe43">
<h4 id="org990fe43">Inkjet components: Ink cartridge</h4>
<ul>
<li>Places drops of ink on the page
<ul>
<li>Pulled from cartridge</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgc077add">
<h4 id="orgc077add">Inkjet components: Print head</h4>
<ul>
<li>Often the print head is integrated into the cartridge</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org0b47611">
<h4 id="org0b47611">Inkjet components: Feed rollers</h4>
<ul>
<li>Pick up and feed paper
<ul>
<li>Can wear down, get dirty</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgf20bf3c">
<h4 id="orgf20bf3c">Inkjet components: Duplexing assembly</h4>
<ul>
<li>Not a part of every printer</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgba3f84a">
<h4 id="orgba3f84a">Inkjet components: Carriage and belt</h4>
<ul>
<li>Ink cartridges move over the paper</li>
<li>Belt moves the carriage back and forth</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org4bd7008">
<h4 id="org4bd7008">Inkjet maintenance: Calibrate</h4>
<ul>
<li>Nozzles need to be aligned to the paper</li>
<li>Usually on-board calibration program</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org02d938c">
<h4 id="org02d938c">Inkjet Maintenance:</h4>
<ul>
<li>Clean heads</li>
<li>Replace cartridges</li>
<li>Calibrate</li>
<li>Clear jams</li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org79f583b">
<h3 id="org79f583b">Thermal Printers</h3>
<ul>
<li>Most often found in commerical settings, printing receipts and other smaller documents</li>

</ul>


<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images/3-11-ThermalPrinterPrintingProcess.jpg" alt="3-11-ThermalPrinterPrintingProcess.jpg" width="75%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 110: </span>Thermal printer printing process</p>
</div>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section>


<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images/3-11-ThermalPrinter.jpg" alt="3-11-ThermalPrinter.jpg" width="50%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 111: </span>A thermal label printer (opened)</p>
</div>

<ul>
<li>Parts: 
<ul>
<li>Feed assembly, heating element</li>
<li>Special thermal paper</li>

</ul></li>
<li>Maintenance: 
<ul>
<li>Replace paper</li>
<li>Clean heating element</li>
<li>Remove debris</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org7b23ffa">
<h3 id="org7b23ffa">Impact printers</h3>
<ul>
<li>The oldest, most classic printers around
<ul>
<li>Dot matrix, daisy wheel</li>
<li>Usually loud and slow</li>
<li>Still used because for some print jobs they can be quite fast</li>
<li>Due to impact printing process, the only kind of printer that can use carbon paper to make multiple copies</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section>
<ul>
<li>Parts:
<ul>
<li>Print head, ribbon, tractor feed</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgcdbec09">
<h4 id="orgcdbec09">Dot matrix printer</h4>
<ul>
<li>Can produce both text and graphics, though neither will look particularly good compared to laser, or even inkjet</li>
<li>Complex sets of tiny pins strike an ink-coated ribbon</li>

</ul>

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images/3-11-DotMatrixPrinter.jpg" alt="3-11-DotMatrixPrinter.jpg" width="30%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 112: </span>Dot matrix printer</p>
</div>
<ul>
<li>These have a distinctive sound, here&rsquo;s a YouTube clip if you&rsquo;ve never heard the relaxing sounds of a dot matrix printer:
<ul>
<li><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cDX3rVuW-7U">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cDX3rVuW-7U</a></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orge94cef2">
<h4 id="orge94cef2">Daisy wheel printer</h4>
<ul>
<li>Almost like an automated old-fashioned typewriter
<ul>
<li>Pre-formed type elements strike paper through an ink-coated ribbon, producing text</li>
<li>In fact, some manual typewriters used daisy wheel print heads</li>
<li>These days, more like a historical curiosity, though they are capable of producing good looking text</li>
<li>Text <b>only</b> - no graphics</li>
<li>So loud!  Here is a YouTube video if you want to hear how they sound:</li>
<li><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CTBM9JELUYQ">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CTBM9JELUYQ</a></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org3f44cdd">
<h4 id="org3f44cdd">Impact printer paper</h4>
<ul>
<li>Can use regular old printer paper</li>
<li>For fast, extensive dot matrix printing can use continuous sheets</li>
<li>Can use carbon copies between pages</li>

</ul>


<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images/3-11-DotMatrixContinuousSheetPaper.jpg" alt="3-11-DotMatrixContinuousSheetPaper.jpg" width="60%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 113: </span>Dot matrix continuous feed paper (this one has carbon copying built in!)</p>
</div>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgc5b1170">
<h4 id="orgc5b1170">Impact printer maintenance:</h4>
<ul>
<li>Replace ribbon</li>
<li>replace print head</li>
<li>replace paper</li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
</section>
<section>
<section id="slide-orgd42460f">
<h2 id="orgd42460f">4.1 â€“ Compare and contrast cloud computing concepts.</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-orgd42460f">
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgb81d338">
<h3 id="orgb81d338">Cloud computing</h3>
<ul>
<li>Services that are housed &ldquo;in the Cloud&rdquo;
<ul>
<li>i.e. on someone else&rsquo;s computer, server, or network</li>
<li>Largest providers of such services today:
<ul>
<li>Google Cloud</li>
<li>Amazon (AWS)</li>
<li>Microsoft (Azure)</li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgef07f6e">
<h3 id="orgef07f6e">&ldquo;The Cloud&rdquo;</h3>
<ul>
<li>What is &ldquo;The Cloud&rdquo;? <i>precisely?</i>
<ul>
<li>As mentioned above, &ldquo;The Cloud&rdquo; is essentially a computer (or network of computers!) that belongs to someone else</li>
<li>And that someone is renting it out to you</li>
<li>The computer that you are renting can act as:
<ul>
<li>a mail server</li>
<li>a file server</li>
<li>a print server</li>
<li>any other kind of server, really</li>

</ul></li>
<li>Sometimes the &ldquo;rent&rdquo; is your personal information
<ul>
<li>i.e., Gmail</li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org2fda24a">
<h3 id="org2fda24a">A momentary definition of The Cloud</h3>
<blockquote>
<p>
The cloud is a suite of hardware and software - managed by a service provider or organization - that provides data, applications, and other resources to users, often via the Internet.
</p>
</blockquote>
<ul>
<li>The kinds of services provided on the cloud, and the ways we think about them, are constantly changing and quite complicated.</li>
<li>Fortunately, the A+ only requires you to know the basic stuff</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orge17aa0e">
<h3 id="orge17aa0e">Cloud Computing</h3>
<ul>
<li>In fact, The A+ only really deals with <code>Cloud Computing</code> which has a more limited definition:
<ul>
<li>&ldquo;Cloud computing is a model for enabling ubiquitous, convenient, on-demand network access to a shared pool of configurable computing resources (e.g., networks, servers, storage, applications, and services) that can be rapidly provisioned and released with minimal management effort or service provider interaction.&rdquo;
<ul>
<li>For the source of the above quote and the standards from which CompTIA gets all of its thinking about cloud computing, go here:
<ul>
<li><a href="https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/Legacy/SP/nistspecialpublication800-145.pdf">NIST definition of cloud computing</a></li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org7ad9fdb">
<h3 id="org7ad9fdb">So, the key is,</h3>
<ul>
<li>from above quote - &ldquo;minimal management effort or service provider interaction.&rdquo;</li>
<li>That&rsquo;s the nice thing about a service like Gmail - it usually works right, you don&rsquo;t have to worry about how to set it up
<ul>
<li>And chances are you&rsquo;ve never had to deal with Google about any aspect of it.</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org433bdf9">
<h3 id="org433bdf9">This means that,</h3>
<ul>
<li>Cloud computing saves money and time
<ul>
<li>You might not need to have an in-house network guy any more</li>
<li>You won&rsquo;t need to have a server room, sucking up electricity and generating heat and further problems</li>
<li>Someone else is responsible for maintaining your stuff
<ul>
<li>Of course, the last can create its own problems&#x2026;</li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org4a7b6dd">
<h3 id="org4a7b6dd"><b>IaaS</b> - Infrastructure as a Service</h3>
<ul>
<li>A service that offers computer networking, storage, load balancing, routing, and VM (virtual machine) hosting
<ul>
<li>The <i>provider</i> hosts all the devious and complicated equipment and software required to manage such things</li>
<li>With a subscription service, you can access hardware only when you need it
<ul>
<li>This model has <i>scalability</i> - you can quickly ramp up the scale of the service without having to buy a bunch of new equipment</li>
<li>Common providers:
<ul>
<li><a href="https://cloud.google.com/">Google Cloud Computing</a></li>
<li><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/">Amazon Web Services</a></li>
<li><a href="https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/">Microsoft Azure</a> <sup><a id="fnr.1" class="footref" href="#fn.1">1</a></sup></li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org957ca6d">
<h3 id="org957ca6d"><b>SaaS</b> - Software as a Service</h3>
<ul>
<li>This is the most commonly used and recognized kind of cloud computing
<ul>
<li>This allows users to access an individual application provided by a third party over the internet</li>
<li>Google is really the master of this service, with <a href="http://mail.google.com">Gmail</a>, <a href="http://docs.google.com">Google Docs</a>, etc</li>
<li>But Microsoft is catching up, with <a href="https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-365">Office 365</a></li>
<li>This means that the applications themselves do not have to be installed on your device, nor do you need to worry about updating them.
<ul>
<li>As someone who has dallied with the idea of setting of their own email server, it is <i>not easy</i> and I am happy to outsource that!</li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org8eadfeb">
<h3 id="org8eadfeb"><b>PaaS</b> - Platform as a Service</h3>
<ul>
<li>This one is slightly trickier for newcomers to understand
<ul>
<li>Renting a fully configured environment can allow developers to work on software without having to manage that environment themselves.</li>
<li>Management, updating, keeping the data secure is all the responsibility of the provider</li>
<li>This is also where the definitions start to break down - is a virtual desktop infrastructure, software, or a platform?</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgc068ca8">
<h3 id="orgc068ca8">Public vs. private vs. hybrid vs. community</h3>
<ul>
<li>These definitions are, again, those defined by <a href="https://www.nist.gov/">NIST</a>
<ul>
<li>They measure how cloud resources are shared and apportioned out by providers</li>
<li>Can also determine how much they cost</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgb62c9b0">
<h4 id="orgb62c9b0">Public cloud</h4>
<ul>
<li>The service provider offers applications and storage space to the general public over the Internet
<ul>
<li>Examples include <a href="https://www.nist.gov/">Dropbox</a>, <a href="http://mail.google.com">Gmail</a>, <a href="https://www.rackspace.com/">Rackspace</a>, and other usual suspects</li>
<li>These services end up being much cheaper - you can rent a tiny little stripped down virtual Linux machine for as little as five dollars per <i>year</i></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orga447b8c">
<h4 id="orga447b8c">Private Cloud</h4>
<ul>
<li>Usually designed specifically for a particular organization or individual
<ul>
<li>Individuals / businesses purchase their own software / hardware to run their own virtualization / cloud service</li>

</ul></li>
<li>Often loses some of the desirable features of cloud computing
<ul>
<li>Not as scaleable, you are now responsible for managing and updating software</li>
<li>BUT! Now you can control your own security, the data all stays on-site</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org8fd1e91">
<h3 id="org8fd1e91">Shared resources</h3>
<ul>
<li>Much of the point of cloud computing is <i>sharing</i> - of resources, cost, responsibilities</li>
<li>And, depending on the model you adapt for your cloud, sharing your data
<ul>
<li>The two basic choices are <b>internal</b> or <b>external</b> cloud architecture</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org715ecbd">
<h3 id="org715ecbd">Internal vs. external clouds</h3>
<ul>
<li>Internal
<ul>
<li>No resources (i.e. servers, bandwidth) are shared</li>
<li>You pay for all that stuff yourself</li>
<li>Also have to maintain it yourself</li>
<li>But you also control it yourself, and most of the costs are up-front</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org3414771">
<h3 id="org3414771">Internal vs. external clouds, cont&rsquo;d</h3>
<ul>
<li>External
<ul>
<li>Resources shared with others on an external cloud</li>
<li>Infrastructure owned by someone else
<ul>
<li>(Who is responsible for keeping it running)</li>

</ul></li>
<li>Generally less expensive;
<ul>
<li>Cost can be monitored over time</li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgda27c0f">
<h3 id="orgda27c0f">Important features of cloud computing</h3>
<ul>
<li>The next few slides / sections are about various features of cloud computing
<ul>
<li>Important to know, but more importantly
<ul>
<li>This is what CompTIA <i>expects</i> you to know:
<ul>
<li><b>rapid elasticity</b></li>
<li><b>on-demand</b> service</li>
<li><b>resource pooling</b></li>
<li><b>measured service</b></li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org2fea59e">
<h3 id="org2fea59e">Rapid elasticity</h3>
<ul>
<li>The ability to:
<ul>
<li>Build a network or resource quickly and efficiently
<ul>
<li>&ldquo;Bob we just launched Widget 2.0 and we will have 2,000 more orders a month!
<ul>
<li>&ldquo;No prob, I&rsquo;ll just spin up 500 new identical webservers by clicking this button!</li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>
<li>Not all providers can provide the kind of elasticity you might want</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org3b834da">
<h3 id="org3b834da">On-demand</h3>
<ul>
<li>On your own, adding new software or hardware can be difficult, expensive, and time-consuming
<ul>
<li>With a cloud service, it can be instant</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgca38e69">
<h3 id="orgca38e69">Resource pooling</h3>
<ul>
<li>The provider&rsquo;s resources can be considered one big pool of stuff - hardware, bandwidth, software
<ul>
<li>The client does not know (or care) where the stuff is
<ul>
<li>They just know what they want from it</li>
<li>The provider can then divvy up its resources: memory, storage, computing power</li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org4f64011">
<h3 id="org4f64011">Measured service</h3>
<ul>
<li>Costs and use are monitored by the provider
<ul>
<li>Data provided to client</li>
<li>Allowing careful assessment and planning of costs and use of the services</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgc500a17">
<h3 id="orgc500a17">Metered vs non-metered</h3>
<ul>
<li>Metered cost: 
<ul>
<li>Everything tracked and with incremental charge
<ul>
<li>Usually including things like bandwidth, storage, number of VMs</li>
<li>Part of <i>rapid elasticity</i> - if you need more bandwidth, you get it quickly but pay for every byte of it</li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>
<li>Non-metered cost:
<ul>
<li>One charge for all services; things like bandwidth and storage are either
<ul>
<li><i>fixed</i> or <i>unlimited</i></li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org74b898a">
<h3 id="org74b898a">Real world examples of measured service</h3>

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images/4-1-azureVMcosts.png" alt="4-1-azureVMcosts.png" width="90%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 114: </span>Azure Windows 10 VM metered cost</p>
</div>

<ul>
<li>Here&rsquo;s my use of an Azure Windows 10 VM, which we will use in class
<ul>
<li>I get charged for bandwidth, storage, and the number of virtual machines I use
<ul>
<li>(You can see how on July 10th I realized I didn&rsquo;t need any storage and turned it off)</li>

</ul></li>
<li>When my virtual machine is on, I am charged; when it is off, no charge
<ul>
<li>You can see the two times I had it on for class</li>

</ul></li>
<li>But don&rsquo;t worry about the cost, you get $200 in credit from Microsoft when you start
<ul>
<li>I did this just to learn about Azure because I had never used it before</li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section>
<ul>
<li>Compare that with the cloud server I use in real life:
<ul>
<li>(which has <i>non-metered cost</i>)</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images/4-1-myCloudServer.png" alt="4-1-myCloudServer.png" width="75%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 115: </span>my cute dedicated server</p>
</div>
<ul>
<li>I pay a fixed amount per month and I get: 
<ul>
<li>unlimited bandwidth</li>
<li>as many VMs as I can cram on there
<ul>
<li>(5 right now)</li>

</ul></li>
<li>1 TB storage</li>

</ul></li>
<li>Nice deal, eh?
<ul>
<li>But I get charged whether I use it or not,
<ul>
<li>Whereas right now I am paying nothing for my Azure VM unless I turn it on</li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org444f46f">
<h3 id="org444f46f">Off-site email applications</h3>
<ul>
<li>This is probably one of the most widely used cloud applications
<ul>
<li>So normalized that you probably don&rsquo;t even realize you&rsquo;re using a cloud service</li>
<li>It is perfect for the cloud service model:
<ul>
<li>Email servers are big, complicated, have huge security issues</li>
<li>Just think about all the spam and phishing that you are generally sheltered from if you use a big provider</li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>
<li>Services offered by Yahoo, Google, Microsoft, <a href="https://www.aol.com/">AOL</a> even!</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org4c40dd8">
<h3 id="org4c40dd8">Cloud file storage services</h3>
<ul>
<li>Also good for a cloud model, and one of the first cloud services ever offered
<ul>
<li>Other people mange your storage and keep it safe</li>
<li>You can access it from anywhere, from any device</li>
<li>Works well for collaboration / sharing</li>
<li>Can synchronize between devices
<ul>
<li>Then you will always have the most current version</li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org61698e7">
<h4 id="org61698e7">Cloud storage providers</h4>
<ul>
<li>There is no lack of these, but here are the biggest players:
<ul>
<li><a href="http://www.dropbox.com">Dropbox</a></li>
<li><a href="https://www.google.com/drive/">Google Drive</a></li>
<li><a href="http://www.icloud.com">Apple iCloud</a></li>
<li><a href="https://onedrive.live.com/">Microsoft OneDrive</a></li>

</ul></li>
<li>Generally all these folks have a free / extremely low cost tier
<ul>
<li>And then they suck you in for more</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orga836ddb">
<h3 id="orga836ddb">Synchronization apps</h3>
<ul>
<li>Google Drive, OneCloud, and iCloud all have versions of this:
<ul>
<li>An app will run on your device (workstation, smartphone, tablet)</li>
<li>The app will monitor your files and update them to the cloud when they change</li>

</ul></li>
<li>I would feel remiss if I did not mention a great open source alternative to these:
<ul>
<li><a href="https://syncthing.net">Syncthing</a>, which can also run on your phone, computer, tablet, whatever</li>
<li>Runs on GUI or CLI</li>
<li>But it can be complicated and not for beginners!
<ul>
<li>(you should take that as a challenge!)</li>
<li>(Syncthing will not be on the A+!)</li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgec58c20">
<h3 id="orgec58c20">Cloud-based applications</h3>
<ul>
<li>The app lives in the cloud, not on your computer
<ul>
<li>Data stored in cloud</li>
<li>As is the application itself</li>
<li>You don&rsquo;t have to update it or manage it</li>
<li>But your data might not be so secure&#x2026;</li>

</ul></li>
<li>Google Docs, Microsoft Office 365 are examples</li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org3105d6a">
<h3 id="org3105d6a">Cloud virtual desktops</h3>
<ul>
<li>Virtual Desktop Infrastructure (VDI)
<ul>
<li>Can connect to as pre-built desktop</li>
<li>Can access from any OS</li>
<li>All information / data local to virtual desktop</li>
<li>Which keeps your personal device isolated and secure</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>


<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
</section>
<section>
<section id="slide-orgaf19d6b">
<h2 id="orgaf19d6b">4.2 â€“ Given a scenario, set up and configure client-side virtualization.</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-orgaf19d6b">
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org30a9c6b">
<h3 id="org30a9c6b">What is a Virtual Machine (VM)?</h3>
<ul>
<li>First of all, cool as heck
<ul>
<li>It is a software-derived computer, but all virtual</li>
<li>This includes the CPU, RAM, accessories</li>
<li>And it lives inside whatever actual, real-world computer is hosting it</li>

</ul></li>
<li>In the past, only one operating system could tun on one computer
<ul>
<li>Now, the number of individual machines and OSs that can run on one computer are limited only by:
<ul>
<li>The power of the CPU</li>
<li>The amount of RAM</li>

</ul></li>
<li>CPU cycles and RAM must be shared between host and VM</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org3ecbb25">
<h3 id="org3ecbb25">Purpose of virtual machines</h3>
<ul>
<li>An example to visualize:
<ul>
<li>One powerful server which can run many virtual machines</li>
<li>Each virtual machine runs an operating system and some applications</li>
<li>Different users can log into the virtual machines and access their own stuff</li>
<li>Virtual machines are what make cloud computing work!</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgabb7e2e">
<h3 id="orgabb7e2e">Resource requirements</h3>
<ul>
<li>CPU processor support:
<ul>
<li>Intel and AMD have their own virtualization technologies:
<ul>
<li>Intel: Virtualization Technology (VT)</li>
<li>AMD: AMD-V</li>
<li>Your CPU must support virtualization</li>

</ul></li>
<li>Memory: must have enough to run your own CPU and your guest CPU</li>
<li>Disk space - the guest machine will need its own space
<ul>
<li>It&rsquo;s a little like having a messy, demanding, entitled roommate</li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org56e77d2">
<h3 id="org56e77d2">Hypervisor</h3>
<ul>
<li>The main part of virtual machine structure
<ul>
<li>A piece of software which allows multiple operating systems to share the same host</li>
<li>Also known as a Virtual Machine Manager (VMM)</li>

</ul></li>
<li>Hypervisors make the whole thing possible</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org1156afc">
<h3 id="org1156afc">Types of hypervisors - type 1</h3>
<ul>
<li>Type 1 Hypervisor
<ul>
<li>Sits directly on the hardware of the host machine</li>
<li>For this reason also known as a <i>bare metal hypervisor</i></li>
<li>Generally faster, more efficient</li>
<li>Most commonly used for server-side virtualization
<ul>
<li>(rather than what you might do on your personal machine)</li>
<li>Because it has few hardware requirements <i>for itself</i></li>
<li>Examples include:
<ul>
<li><a href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/virtualization/hyper-v/hyper-v-technology-overview">Microsoft Hyper-V</a></li>
<li><a href="https://www.vmware.com/products/esxi-and-esx.html">VMware ESXi</a></li>
<li>an open source hypervisor: <a href="https://www.linux-kvm.org/page/Main_Page">Linux KVM</a></li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org879a443">
<h3 id="org879a443">Types of hypervisors - type 2</h3>
<ul>
<li>Type 2 hypervisor
<ul>
<li>Sits on top of an existing operating system</li>
<li>Software to run virtual machines</li>
<li>More likely to be the kind of thing you use
<ul>
<li>(which you should!)</li>

</ul></li>
<li>Examples include:
<ul>
<li><a href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/958559/description-of-windows-virtual-pc">Windows Virtual PC</a> - older, ran on Windows 7!</li>
<li><a href="https://www.vmware.com/products/workstation-pro/workstation-pro-evaluation.html">VMware Workstation</a></li>
<li>And of course a free open source Type 2 hypervisor: <a href="https://www.virtualbox.org/">Oracle VirtualBox</a>
<ul>
<li>This is what I used in class on my own machine to show you some things</li>
<li>Try it out!</li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orge275b70">
<h3 id="orge275b70">An example of a Type 2 hypervisor running</h3>

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images/4-2-VBoxUbuntuMateMyMachine.png" alt="4-2-VBoxUbuntuMateMyMachine.png" width="95%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 116: </span>Ubuntu Mate 18.04 running on a MacBook (Catalina)</p>
</div>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgbe38d48">
<h3 id="orgbe38d48">Emulator requirements</h3>
<ul>
<li>Emulators are different from VMs</li>
<li>Running original code to run on a different machine
<ul>
<li>i.e. running a Windows 7 program on a Mac</li>
<li>Difficult, often much slower and almost unmanageable</li>
<li>The shortcomings of emulation is why VMs exist</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org7b3e64a">
<h3 id="org7b3e64a">Security requirements</h3>
<ul>
<li>No VM vulnerabilities yet, but boy this has potential
<ul>
<li>Imagine the VM escaping into its host</li>
<li>Could conceivable infect other VMs</li>
<li>Each VM needs to run its own firewall and antiviral anti-malware solution</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgc708299">
<h3 id="orgc708299">Network requirements</h3>
<ul>
<li>Client-side VMs have their own virtual (internal) networks</li>
<li><b>Shared network address</b>
<ul>
<li>Each guest VM uses a private internal IP</li>
<li>And uses the guest IP through NAT <a href="#slide-NAT" class="backwardlink">see earlier slide</a></li>

</ul></li>
<li><b>Bridged network address</b>
<ul>
<li>The VM exists as a device on the physical network (LAN)</li>

</ul></li>
<li><b>Private network address</b>
<ul>
<li>The VM cannot communicate outside its host</li>
<li>(this is the most secure route, but not as useful)</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
</section>
<section>
<section id="slide-org9acbd3c">
<h2 id="org9acbd3c">5.1 â€“ Given a scenario, use the best practice methodology to resolve problems.</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-org9acbd3c">
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orga4086be">
<h3 id="orga4086be">Step 0: Think about the context</h3>
<p>
Always consider corporate policies, procedures, and impacts before implementing changes
</p>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org484bfe5">
<h3 id="org484bfe5">1. Identify the problem</h3>
<ul>
<li>Question the user and identify user changes to computer and perform backups before making
changes</li>
<li>Inquire regarding environmental or infrastructure changes</li>
<li>Review system and application logs</li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org1ee60e6">
<h3 id="org1ee60e6">2. Establish a theory of probable cause (question the obvious)</h3>
<ul>
<li>If necessary, conduct external or internal research based on symptoms</li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org019ee12">
<h3 id="org019ee12">3. Test the theory to determine cause</h3>
<ul>
<li>Once the theory is confirmed, determine the next steps to resolve problem</li>
<li>If theory is not confirmed, establish new theory or escalate</li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org0d8b67c">
<h3 id="org0d8b67c">4. Establish a plan of action to resolve the problem and implement the solution</h3>
<ul>
<li>Build the plan
<ul>
<li>Calculate and document impact of solution</li>
<li>Backup / backout if things go bad</li>

</ul></li>
<li>Fix it!</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgc9eb022">
<h3 id="orgc9eb022">5. Verify full system functionality and, if applicable, implement preventive measures</h3>
<ul>
<li>Restart the machine</li>
<li>Confirm the fix</li>
<li>Discuss with user</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgf4f0078">
<h3 id="orgf4f0078">6. Document findings, actions, and outcomes</h3>
<ul>
<li>Contribute to knowledge base</li>
<li>Useful if problem occurs again</li>
<li>In a legal sense, didn&rsquo;t happen until you document it</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org2f9c737">
<h3 id="org2f9c737">A flowchart</h3>

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images/5-1-HowToTroubleshootDiagram.png" alt="5-1-HowToTroubleshootDiagram.png" width="95%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 117: </span>Troubleshooting flowchart</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
